late 1938, Szilard immediately thought, hey, you could probably use this to make a chain reaction. And if you could make a chain reaction, you might be able to make nuclear weapons. Scientists in many countries went to their leaders and said, \"You know, \"maybe this is something we should be worried about.\" And the person who did that in the United States was Leo Szilard. Nobody knew who Leo Szilard was in 1939, but they did know his very good friend, Albert Einstein. So Szilard went to Einstein and said, \"Let's write a letter.\" And they ended up writing a letter to President Roosevelt that essentially said, \"Hey, \"there's been these new discoveries in science. \"There is a possibility of a very large weapon being made. \"Somebody should be looking at this.\" Roosevelt was given this letter, and he agreed, \"Sure.\" He created the uranium committee, a very small scale research project where the goal is to just find out, are atomic bombs gonna be a problem? Einstein was a name that they were thinking of making on the uranium committee. You can actually find versions of their early notes on this, but then they cross it out. And they decided not to bring him in on the project. And they had sort of two reasons for this. One was Einstein's politics were pretty far to the left of what was considered proper at the time, and this was enough to get him a very large FBI file by itself. The other reason is he is an older scientist at this point, and the kind of work that Einstein did is not about practical, how do you build a plant to make enriched uranium? It's not that kind of physics. Even his famous equation, E = MC squared, it doesn't really tell you how to build a bomb. It doesn't even tell you if a bomb could be built. It just tells you that an atomic bomb is not gonna violate the laws of conservation of mass and energy, which is a useful thing to know. But it's sort of like saying Newton's equations don't tell you whether or not you can go to Mars or not, but they're useful if you are happening to go on the way to Mars. So Einstein's role in the project was a lot less than I think most people think, but he did have this one interesting bit at the very beginning of writing this letter."}],"croppedPreviewImage":"https://hips.hearstapps.com/vidthumb/images/einstein-thumbnail-64b9826e1ad39.png?crop=1.00xw:1.00xh;0,0","description":"Albert Einstein played a key role in jumpstarting the US's research into nuclear weapons.","duration":147,"title":"Einstein's Real Role in the Manhattan Project","created_at":"2023-07-20T20:07:58.132920Z","transcodings":[{"mapped_preset_name":"rover_16x9_240p_sd"},{"mapped_preset_name":"rover_16x9_360p_sd"},{"mapped_preset_name":"rover_16x9_720p_hd"},{"mapped_preset_name":"rover_16x9_480p_sd"},{"full_url":"https://streaming.hearstdigitalstudios.com/2ef8925b-1644-4a71-b290-e0221289276f/video_rover_16x9_1080p_hd_1689878042_7941.mp4","mapped_preset_name":"rover_16x9_1080p_hd"},{}],"nearest_aspect_ratio":"16:9"},{"id":"51af7a53-cfb8-45c2-91df-6daa9ce70b87","role":4,"media_id":"e89e023e-b016-476f-8627-7095523a150c","media_type":"image","hips_url":"https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod/images/albert-einstein-sticks-out-his-tongue-when-asked-by-news-photo-1681316749.jpg","hips_prefix":"hmg-prod","metadata":{"crops":{"1x1":"1xw:0.78905xh;center,top","2x1":"1xw:0.39453xh;center,top","3x1":"1xw:0.26302xh;center,top","4x3":"1xw:0.59179xh;center,top","4x6":"0.84489xw:1xh;center,top","5x1":"1xw:0.15781xh;center,top","6x4":"1xw:0.52604xh;center,top","8x1":"1xw:0.09863xh;center,top","10x2":"1xw:0.15781xh;center,top","10x3":"1xw:0.23672xh;center,top","10x5":"1xw:0.39453xh;center,top","16x9":"1xw:0.44384xh;center,top","8x10":"1xw:0.98632xh;center,top","9x16":"0.71288xw:1xh;center,top","18x11":"1xw:0.4822xh;center,top","original":"1.00xw:0.956xh;0,0.0437xh"},"embed_image_link_url":"","embed_image_link_title":"","embed_image_link_new_tab":"0","embed_image_link_nofollow":"1"},"image_metadata":{"seo_meta_description":"alb